  1. This dataset is the complete customer list. This means what you determined above is the real mean. Now we want to use your other skills you learned during this semester (i.e. sampling, inference, confidence intervals) to figure out the mean without using the entire customer list.

6.1. Sampling

First, we need to draw a random sample from the dataset. The size of this sample depends on the size of our dataset and the level of precision we need. A common rule of thumb is to use a sample size that is large enough to be representative of the population but small enough to be practical.

set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility
sample_size <- 100  # Size of sample data
sample_data <- Cybercost[sample(nrow(Cybercost), sample_size), ]

6.2. Calculate Sample Mean Calculate the mean of “Cost P/M” from sample. This is point estimate.

sample_mean <- mean(sample_data$`Cost.P.M`, na.rm = TRUE)

6.3. Calculate Standard Error The standard error of the mean is a measure of the amount of variability in the sampling distribution of the mean. It can be calculated as the standard deviation of the sample divided by the square root of the sample size.

standard_error <- sd(sample_data$`Cost.P.M`, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(sample_size)
alpha <- 0.05
t_critical <- qt(alpha/2, df = sample_size-1, lower.tail = FALSE)
confidence_interval <- c(sample_mean - t_critical * standard_error, sample_mean + t_critical * standard_error)

Findings

  • The modeling and statistical methods described laid the foundation for estimating population density ‘excluding P/M’ from the model. Estimation of the error of the standard and subsequent construction of the confidence interval yield the expected range of actual monthly costs due to the choice and use of an alpha value of 0.05, with a confidence level of 95% at t-1. divide it appropriately for small samples.

  • These confidence intervals determine the sampling variable and encompass the mean of the sample, forming a statistical measure of the population mean ‘including P/M’.

  1. Take multiple random samples of the customer list. Plot the sample means, confidence levels, real means, etc. on the same plots as they did in your textbook for each random sample
actual_mean <- mean(Cybercost$`Cost.P.M`, na.rm = TRUE)
calculate_sample_stats <- function(sample_size, data) {
  sample_data <- data[sample(nrow(data), sample_size), ]
  sample_mean <- mean(sample_data$`Cost.P.M`, na.rm = TRUE)
  standard_error <- sd(sample_data$`Cost.P.M`, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(sample_size)
  t_critical <- qt(0.025, df = sample_size - 1, lower.tail = FALSE)
  confidence_interval <- c(sample_mean - t_critical * standard_error, sample_mean + t_critical * standard_error)
  return(list(mean = sample_mean, lower = confidence_interval[1], upper = confidence_interval[2]))
}
set.seed(123)  # Ensuring reproducibility.
sample_sizes <- c(30, 50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300)  #We can Adjust sizes as needed
sample_stats <- lapply(sample_sizes, function(size) calculate_sample_stats(size, Cybercost))
plot_data <- data.frame(
  SampleSize = rep(sample_sizes, each = length(sample_stats)),
  Mean = sapply(sample_stats, function(x) x$mean),
  LowerCI = sapply(sample_stats, function(x) x$lower),
  UpperCI = sapply(sample_stats, function(x) x$upper)
)
# Creating a plot using the ggplot2 library.
# plots 'Mean' against 'SampleSize' from the 'plot_data' dataset.
# 'geom_point()' adds scatter plot points, colored based on the 'Mean' value.

#  using 'LowerCI' and 'UpperCI' for the confidence interval range,

# 'geom_hline()' draws a horizontal dashed line at 'actual_mean', in red, representing the population mean.
# 'scale_color_gradient()' sets the color gradient for points from purple (low values) to blue (high values).
# 'labs()' sets the plot title and labels for the x and y axes, 
#  with a focus on comparing sample means and confidence intervals against the population mean.
# 'theme_minimal()' applies a minimalistic theme for a clean and readable presentation.

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = SampleSize, y = Mean, color = Mean)) + 
  geom_point() +  
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = LowerCI, ymax = UpperCI), width = 0.1) +  
  geom_hline(yintercept = actual_mean, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +  
  scale_color_gradient(low = "purple", high = "blue") + 
  labs(title = "Sample Means and Confidence Intervals vs. Population Mean",
       x = "Sample Size",
       y = "Mean Cost P/M") +
  theme_minimal()

Findings

  • Correlation with population mean: As the sample size increases, the sample tends to stabilize closer to the population mean, indicated by red dashed lines This indicates that larger samples provide more accurate estimates of the population

  • Decreasing confidence interval: The confidence interval around the sample shows narrowing as the sample size increases. This means that estimates of the mean “cost P/M” are more accurate in larger sample sizes.

t_test_result <- t.test(small_companies$`Cost.P.M`, large_companies$`Cost.P.M`, alternative = "greater", na.rm = TRUE)
# The code segments the 'Cybercost' dataset into two groups based on the number of users
# :small and large companies.
# 'small_companies' includes rows where 'Users' is less than 1000.
# 'large_companies' includes rows where 'Users' is equal to or greater than 1000.
# 'drop = FALSE' parameter ensures that the data structure remains a dataframe even if there's only one column.
# 't.test()' performs a two-sample t-test comparing the small and large companies.
# It tests the hypothesis that the mean of the first group is greater than the second group.
# Finally, 't_test_result' is printed to check the results of the t-test.

small_companies <- Cybercost[Cybercost$Users < 1000, , drop = FALSE]
large_companies <- Cybercost[Cybercost$Users >= 1000, , drop = FALSE]
t_test_result <- t.test(small_companies, large_companies, alternative = "greater")
t_test_result

  • The Welch Two Sample t-test indicates that large companies have a significantly higher mean value than small companies, with the mean for large companies being 655.0563 compared to 169.2910 for small companies.

New Hypothesis:

Null Hypothesis [H0]: There is no correlation between the number of security attacks and the cost per month.

Alternative Hypothesis [H1]:There is a positive correlation between the number of security attacks and the cost per month.

The reasoning behind this hypothesis is that companies experiencing more security attacks might incur higher costs due to increased security measures, insurance, etc.

To test this hypothesis, we need to perform a correlation test and also a linear regression analysis to see if there is a statistically significant relationship between Attacks and Cost P/M.

cor_test <- cor.test(Cybercost$Attacks, Cybercost$`Cost.P.M`, method = "pearson", use = "complete.obs")
regression_model <- lm(`Cost.P.M` ~ Attacks, data = Cybercost)
summary(regression_model)
